## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## whats-next-skills-gen (ad-hoc, throwaway)
##
## DOGFOOD TEST. Runs ONE agent node on claw + openai/gpt-5.5 with
## the full agentic tool-use loop (read + write filesystem, shell).
## Goal: produce 5 SKILL.md files under the whats-next bundle.
##
## This is intentionally a single-node workflow so the dogfood signal
## is unambiguous: if claw-code-go's OpenAI agentic loop works, the
## agent will call read_file/glob/grep many times, then write_file at
## least 5 times. If it fails (e.g. tool dispatch on /v1/responses,
## reasoning_effort + tools interaction, stream aggregation), the
## events.jsonl will show exactly where.
##
## Run:
##   devbox run -- iterion run scripts/adhoc/whats-next-skills-gen.iter
##
## Tail (in a second terminal):
##   tail -F .iterion/runs/<run-id>/events.jsonl | jq '.'
##
## After a green run, commit the produced skills/*.md files. This
## .iter file stays in scripts/adhoc/ as the seed for a future
## examples/whats-next/generate-skills.bot (formalised version, run
## any time we want to refresh / add a skill).
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  skills_dir:    string = "examples/whats-next/skills"

schema gen_output:
  summary:    string
  generated:  json

prompt gen_skills_system:
  You are generating a small set of Claude Code skills (SKILL.md
  files) that will ship inside an iterion .botz bundle named
  whats-next. The skills are markdown reference documents Claude
  Code will load on demand to help an orchestrator bot decide what
  to do next on a given repository.

  Each skill MUST be a single markdown file. Start the file with a
  YAML frontmatter block delimited by lines containing only three
  hyphens. The frontmatter MUST contain exactly two keys:
    - name: a kebab-case slug
    - description: one short, specific sentence. Claude Code uses
      this description to decide whether to load the skill at
      runtime, so be concrete — say what the skill is for, not just
      what topic it covers.

  After the closing frontmatter delimiter, write the body of the
  skill: a level-1 markdown heading with a human-readable title,
  then imperative-voice instructions with numbered lists where
  helpful, and concrete examples drawn from the actual codebase you
  explored. No filler. No marketing prose.

  Target directory for the files: the value of skills_dir below.

  Write exactly these 5 files. Use the listed filename for each.

  1. repo-survey.md — a systematic checklist for surveying an
     unknown repository. Cover: top-level directory map; build /
     dependency files (Taskfile.yml, devbox.json, go.mod,
     package.json, etc.); recent commit activity via
     git log -n 20 --oneline; ADRs under docs/adr/ if present; open
     TODO and FIXME markers; conventions (CLAUDE.md, README.md,
     CONTRIBUTING.md).

  2. iterion-bot-catalog.md — an index of the iterion bots that
     ship in examples/. Inspect these three files in particular:
       - examples/whole_improve_loop/main.bot
       - examples/feature_dev/main.bot
       - examples/secured-renovacy/main.bot
     For each: one-line purpose, key inputs from the workflow vars
     block, the shape of its iterion run invocation, and a "use
     this when …" recommendation rule. This skill is
     iterion-specific.

  3. roadmap-synthesis.md — how to compose a roadmap recommendation
     with three components (long_term, short_term, next_action)
     from a repo survey plus the user's stated priorities. Cover:
     how to weigh urgency vs importance; when to defer; how to pick
     exactly ONE next action — the bot should never recommend more
     than one immediate action.

  4. priority-elicitation.md — question patterns for drawing out a
     user's real priorities in a free-text exchange. Cover: open
     versus forced-choice questions; surfacing blockers; what to do
     when the user is vague; how to mirror back the priorities for
     confirmation.

  5. iterion-dsl-quickref.md — distilled iterion DSL cheatsheet.
     Cover: node types (agent, judge, router, join, human, tool,
     compute, done, fail); edge syntax (the arrow, when conditions,
     bounded loop counters with the "as" keyword, the with-mapping
     form for passing data); reference syntax for accessing vars,
     node outputs, input fields, and loop history (you'll find the
     truth in docs/dsl.md); the budget block; the sandbox modes.
     Cite docs/dsl.md and the example bots as source of truth.

  Approach:
  1. Explore the workspace first with read-only tools (bash, glob,
     grep, read_file). Do NOT write from memory — every claim in a
     skill must trace to a real file you read.
  2. Once you have enough material per skill, call write_file to
     emit it into the skills_dir directory.
  3. Keep each skill under ~150 lines. Concise beats exhaustive.
  4. Do NOT modify any file outside the skills_dir directory.

  When all 5 files are written, return a final structured response
  matching the gen_output schema with a one-paragraph summary and a
  generated array listing one entry per skill produced (filename
  and a short summary of what's in it).

prompt gen_skills_user:
  Generate the 5 skill files now.

  Workspace to explore: {{vars.workspace_dir}}

  Target directory (write each SKILL.md into this directory using
  write_file): {{vars.skills_dir}}

  Begin by listing the top-level directories of the workspace, then
  drill into the relevant areas per skill. Do not skip exploration —
  the dogfood test measures whether you actually use the agentic
  tool loop on real files.

agent generate_skills:
  ## Pinned to claw backend because the dogfood test is specifically
  ## "does claw-code-go's OpenAI agentic loop work on a real
  ## multi-step file-mutation task". Don't fall back to claude_code.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  reasoning_effort: "high"
  output: gen_output
  system: gen_skills_system
  user: gen_skills_user
  ## Snake_case is the claw convention. write_file is the mutation
  ## tool the agent needs to emit each skill file.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, glob, grep]
  ## Skill exploration is multi-step (~30-40 reads/greps before each
  ## write). 60 leaves headroom for retries / re-reads.
  tool_max_steps: 60

workflow whats_next_skills_gen:
  entry: generate_skills

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "30m"
    max_cost_usd: 8.0

  generate_skills -> done
